Introduction（week2）：
In recent years, the rapid proliferation of GenAI and LLMs has had an unprecedented influence on people's lives and society as a whole. However, this technological development also causes many problems. One of the most important problems is that ethics and regulation have failed to keep pace, leading to various social issues, such as copyright infringement and data violation. To deal with these crises, many technology companies have created "responsible AI" guidelines and "soft law." But most of these methods are voluntary and non-binding. Therefore, the main purpose of this report is to show that, driven by capital and commercial interests, these soft laws are doomed to fail and become mere "ethics washing" for enterprises.

To clarify the premise of this report and establish a foundational understanding, it is essential to define several core concepts. Generative AI (GenAI) and Large Language Models (LLMs) are fundamentally data-driven systems that rely heavily on the ingestion and processing of massive datasets to function effectively. Furthermore, in this context, "soft law" refers to voluntary principles, ethical guidelines, and self-regulatory frameworks that explicitly lack legal enforceability and punitive measures. Finally, "ethics washing" occurs when enterprises superficially comply with these soft laws, utilizing them as a public relations facade to evade strict government regulation while relentlessly pursuing profit maximization. This dynamic directly precipitates the core crisis discussed in the subsequent sections of this report.

The fundamental issue with soft law in practice is that it lacks enforcement mechanisms, as highlighted by Hagendorff (2020). This creates a tension between ethics and business; when there are conflicts between ethical responsibility and profit maximization, enterprises will not hesitate to prioritize commercial interests over ethical responsibilities. To investigate this, this report employs a literature review, case study analysis, and empirical data. The scope of this research focuses on the controversy over generative AI training datasets, and will propose mandatory third-party algorithmic auditing as a concrete alternative. Specifically, this report draws on Australia's AI Ethics Principles (S1) to evaluate how government-led voluntary frameworks work in practice. Even though S1 sets clear and positive goals for AI adoption, it lacks real regulatory teeth. This exposes it to the exact flaws Hagendorff (S2) highlights in his critique of AI ethics guidelines. By comparing these two sources, this research will demonstrate how tech companies can easily bypass well-intentioned national guidelines when driven by fierce market pressure.
To systematically investigate these problems, the report is structured as follows: Section 2 explores the theoretical failure of soft law and conducts a comparative analysis in combination with Hagendorff's assessment framework. Subsequently, Section 3 will use the empirical data provided by Bloomberg to provide evidence, revealing the vast chasm between corporate ethical commitments and actual business practices. Furthermore, Section 4 will delve into the technical aspects, providing a technical critique about how ethics washing occurs in data collection, exemplified by the LAION-5B dataset. Finally, Section 5 will propose mandatory third-party algorithmic auditing as the ultimate solution to this crisis. Concluding remarks will summarize the entire text, reiterating the importance of the transition from soft law to hard law.
